# Project lifecycle and publish guards

Use the repository **README**, section *Project management*, for the full workflow. When working inside `**/projects/**/config.json` or publishing repair content:

Respect the *client privacy* rule: **no customer names, phones, or emails** in project files — except **`googleReview.authorName`** (first name + last initial only, e.g. `Howard C.`).

## Explicit publish commands only

Do **not** begin a publish-oriented workflow (preview for go-live, posting, or promoting a project on the **public** site) until the user says so in an **explicit** form, e.g.:

- `publish 0001 to facebook`
- `publish 0001 to webpage`
- `publish 0001 to social media` *(then list intended platforms in the preview — e.g. Facebook, Instagram, Threads)*
- `publish 0001 to social media and webpage`

**Then:** show a **preview summary** and get **confirmation** before any public action (see the *human confirmation* rule). “Ready to post” chit-chat is **not** a trigger.

## No HTML work unless you ask

Do **not** **create** or **edit** any **`*.html`** files (site pages, repair pages, `index.html`, `contact.html`, snippets, etc.) unless the user **explicitly** asks for HTML / site-page work in that conversation.

That includes drive-by fixes (typos, meta tags, nav links, formatting) — **skip them** unless the request is clearly about changing HTML.

**Allowed** examples:

- They include **`webpage`** in an approved `publish <id> to …` flow (after preview + confirm), **or**
- A direct request such as “change `contact.html`”, “fix the menu in `index.html`”, “create the HTML page for 0001”, “add project 0001 to the website”.

Otherwise stick to `config.json`, README, rules, captions-in-chat, or non-HTML files. If unsure, **ask** before touching `*.html`.

## Status (owner-controlled)

- The **`status`** field is **set only by the human** (e.g. `WIP`, `DONE`). Never infer `DONE` from images or narrative alone.
- **`DONE` gate:** Do **not** publish a project to **any** social channel (Facebook, Threads, Instagram, etc.) and do **not** add or update the **public website** so this project becomes visible to visitors, unless that project’s `config.json` has **`status` exactly `"DONE"`**.
  - If `status` is missing or not `DONE`, **stop** and ask the user to confirm when the project is `DONE` before publishing or going live on the site.

## URLs record what is already live

Per-project `config.json` URL fields (`facebookUrl`, `instagramUrl`, `threadUrl`, `youtubeUrl`, `youtubeShortUrl`, `webpageUrl`):

- **`null`** (or absent) → nothing recorded for that channel yet.
- **Non-null URL** → treat as **already published / linked** for that channel. **Do not** create a second post there without **explicit** user instruction (e.g. “repost anyway”).
- After the user approves publishing and a post exists: **update** the matching field with the final permalink.
- **YouTube:** If the user manually uploads a video, **update** `youtubeUrl` and/or `youtubeShortUrl` when they provide the link (no new upload by the agent unless they ask and approve).

## Public project page and links

- **`webpageUrl`** — When a dedicated repair page exists on the main site, store its canonical URL here. Site markup should use **`facebookUrl`**, **`instagramUrl`**, **`threadUrl`**, **YouTube fields**, and **`webpageUrl`** as **`href` targets** where each is non-null — but **do not create or edit `*.html`** to add that unless the user explicitly requested HTML work (see *No HTML work unless you ask*).
- Changing **HTML/CSS/JS** so a **non–`DONE`** project becomes visible on the public site counts as violating the **`DONE` gate** above.

## Order of operations

1. Human uses an **explicit** `publish <id> to …` instruction (and sets **`status`** to `"DONE"` when they want promotion allowed).
2. Agent replies with a **preview summary**; human **confirms** (see *human confirmation* rule).
3. **Content validation** must pass first — run `node scripts/validate-publish.mjs <id>` (see *publish content guards* rule and [`docs/publish-content-guards.md`](../../docs/publish-content-guards.md)).
4. For **`webpage`** (or combined **social media and webpage**): when the owner supplies **`repairDetails`**, write **`repairDetails`** and **refresh `title` + `description`** in `config.json` in the same pass (slogan title; short story lead for `description` — not a skill list). Then run **`node scripts/publish-webpage.mjs <id>`** first (add **`--rotate <file> --cw|--ccw|--180`** or **`--exif-orient`** when the owner reports sideways images); then author/update **`index.html`** if needed. Format **`repairDetails`** and **`itemDetails`** as **multiple paragraphs** — blank line in JSON, one `<p>` each on the page (see [`docs/website-go-live.md`](../../docs/website-go-live.md)).
   - **Manual image renames only** (owner edited filenames in the folder): run **`node scripts/sync-project-story-images.mjs <id>`** — **not** **`normalize-project-media-names.mjs`**. See [`.cursor/rules/project-images-manual-rename.mdc`](project-images-manual-rename.mdc).
5. **Google review:** If the project has **`googleReview`**, **`publish-webpage.mjs`** syncs the **review block** onto **`index.html`** before release (`--no-story-review` to skip) and rebuilds **`new/testimonials.html`** with a **Repair:** link when the story is live (`--no-testimonials` to skip). See [`google-review-testimonial-workflow.mdc`](google-review-testimonial-workflow.mdc).
6. After go-live, **persist** returned permalinks in `config.json` (commits still need separate confirmation).
